dom-domtokenlist-contains.name: contains
dom-domtokenlist-contains.summary: The contains() method of the DOMTokenList interface returns a Boolean  true if the underlying list contains the given token, otherwise false.
dom-domtokenlist-contains.title: DOMTokenList.contains()

domtokenlist.name: entries
domtokenlist.summary: The DOMTokenList.entries() method returns an iterator allowing you to go through all key/value pairs contained in this object. The values are DOMString objects, each representing a single token.
domtokenlist.title: DOMTokenList.entries()

domtokenlist.name: forEach
domtokenlist.summary: The forEach() method of the DOMTokenList interface calls the callback given in parameter once for each value pair in the list, in insertion order.
domtokenlist.title: DOMTokenList.forEach()

domtokenlist.name: keys
domtokenlist.summary: The keys() method of the DOMTokenList interface returns an iterator allowing to go through all keys contained in this object. The keys are of type unsigned integer.
domtokenlist.title: DOMTokenList.keys()

domtokenlist.name: values
domtokenlist.summary: The values() method of the DOMTokenList interface returns an iterator allowing developers to go through all values contained in the DOMTokenList. The individual values are DOMString objects.
domtokenlist.title: DOMTokenList.values()

dom-domtokenlist-item.name: item
dom-domtokenlist-item.summary: The item() method of the DOMTokenList interface returns an item in the list by its index.
dom-domtokenlist-item.title: DOMTokenList.item()

dom-domtokenlist-length.name: length
dom-domtokenlist-length.summary: The length read-only property of the DOMTokenList interface is an integer representing the number of objects stored in the object.
dom-domtokenlist-length.title: DOMTokenList.length

dom-domtokenlist-remove.name: remove
dom-domtokenlist-remove.summary: The remove() method of the DOMTokenList interface removes the specified tokens from the list.
dom-domtokenlist-remove.title: DOMTokenList.remove()

dom-domtokenlist-replace.name: replace
dom-domtokenlist-replace.summary: The replace() method of the DOMTokenList interface replaces an existing token with a new token. If the first token doesn't exist, replace() returns false immediately, without adding the new token to the token list.
dom-domtokenlist-replace.title: DOMTokenList.replace()

dom-domtokenlist-toggle.name: toggle
dom-domtokenlist-toggle.summary: The toggle() method of the DOMTokenList interface removes a given token from the list and returns false. If token doesn't exist it's added and the function returns true.
dom-domtokenlist-toggle.title: DOMTokenList.toggle()

dom-domtokenlist-value.name: value
dom-domtokenlist-value.summary: The value property of the DOMTokenList interface is a stringifier that returns the value of the list as a DOMString, or clears and sets the list to the given value.

dom-element-getelementsbytagnamens.summary: The Element.getElementsByTagNameNS() method returns a live HTMLCollection of elements with the given tag name belonging to the given namespace. It is similar to Document.getElementsByTagNameNS, except that its search is restricted to descendants of the specified element.

chrome.notes: Initially, this method was returning a NodeList; it was then changed to reflect the spec change.

notes: The behavior of element.getElementsByTagNameNS changed between Firefox 3.5 and Firefox 3.6. In Firefox 3.5 and before, this function would automatically case-fold any queries so that a search for "foo" would match "Foo" or "foo". In Firefox 3.6 and later this function is now case-sensitive so that a query for "foo" will only match "foo" and not "Foo". For more background on this, please see the comment from Henri Sivonen about the change. You can also look at the relevant part of the standard, which states which parts of the API are case-sensitive and which parts aren't.

dom-event-currenttarget.name: currentTarget
dom-event-currenttarget.summary: The currentTarget read-only property of the Event interface identifies the current target for the event, as the event traverses the DOM. dom-mutationobserverinit-childlist.summary: The MutationObserverInit dictionary's optional childList property indicates whether or not to monitor the specified node or nodes for the addition or removal of new child nodes.
dom-mutationobserverinit-childlist.title: MutationObserverInit.childList

dom-mutationobserverinit-subtree.name: subtree
dom-mutationobserverinit-subtree.summary: The MutationObserverInit dictionary's optional subtree property can be set to true to monitor the targeted node and all of its descendants.
dom-mutationobserverinit-subtree.title: MutationObserverInit.subtree

dictdef-mutationobserverinit.name: MutationObserverInit
dictdef-mutationobserverinit.summary: The MutationObserverInit dictionary describes the configuration of a mutation observer. As such, it's primarily used as the type of the options parameter on the MutationObserver.observe() method.
dictdef-mutationobserverinit.title: MutationObserverInit

mutationrecord.name: MutationRecord
mutationrecord.summary: A MutationRecord represents an individual DOM mutation. It is the object that is passed to MutationObserver's callback.
mutationrecord.title: MutationRecord

interface-namednodemap.name: NamedNodeMap
interface-namednodemap.summary: The NamedNodeMap interface represents a collection of Attr objects. Objects inside a NamedNodeMap are not in any particular order, unlike NodeList, although they may be accessed by an index as in an array.
interface-namednodemap.title: NamedNodeMap

dom-node-appendchild.name: appendChild
dom-node-appendchild.summary: The Node.appendChild() method adds a node to the end of the list of children of a specified parent node. If the given child is a reference to an existing node in the document, appendChild() moves it from its current position to the new position (there is no requirement to remove the node from its parent node before appending it to some other node).
dom-node-appendchild.title: Node.appendChild()

dom-node-baseuri.name: baseURI
dom-node-baseuri.summary: The baseURI read-only property returns the absolute base URL of a Node.
dom-node-baseuri.title: Node.baseURI

dom-node-childnodes.name: childNodes
dom-node-childnodes.summary: The Node.childNodes read-only property returns a live NodeList of child nodes of the given element where the first child node is assigned index 0.
dom-node-childnodes.title: Node.childNodes

dom-node-clonenode.name: cloneNode
dom-node-clonenode.summary: The Node.cloneNode() method returns a duplicate of the node on which this method was called.
dom-node-clonenode.title: Node.cloneNode()

dom-node-comparedocumentposition.name: compareDocumentPosition
dom-node-comparedocumentposition.summary: The Node.compareDocumentPosition() method reports the position of the given node relative to another node in any document  not just the given nodes document.

ie.notes: Only supports contains for elements

dom-node-comparedocumentposition.title: Node.compareDocumentPosition()

dom-node-contains.name: contains
dom-node-contains.summary: The Node.contains() method returns a Boolean value indicating whether a node is a descendant of a given node, i.e. the node itself, one of its direct children (childNodes), one of the children's direct children, and so on.

ie.notes: Only supported for HTMLElement, not all Node objects.

dom-node-contains.title: Node.contains()

dom-node-firstchild.name: firstChild
dom-node-firstchild.summary: The Node.firstChild read-only property returns the node's first child in the tree, or null if the node has no children.
dom-node-firstchild.title: Node.firstChild

dom-node-getrootnode.name: getRootNode
dom-node-getrootnode.summary: The getRootNode() method of the Node interface returns the context object's root, which optionally includes the shadow root if it is available.
dom-node-getrootnode.title: Node.getRootNode()

dom-node-haschildnodes.name: hasChildNodes
dom-node-haschildnodes.summary: The Node.hasChildNodes() method returns a Boolean value indicating whether the given Node has child nodes or not.
dom-node-haschildnodes.title: Node.hasChildNodes()

dom-node-insertbefore.name: insertBefore
dom-node-insertbefore.summary: The Node.insertBefore() method inserts a node before a reference node as a child of a specified parent node.
dom-node-insertbefore.title: Node.insertBefore()

dom-node-isconnected.name: isConnected
dom-node-isconnected.summary: The isConnected read-only property of the Node interface returns a boolean indicating whether the node is connected (directly or indirectly) to the context object, for example the Document object in the case of the normal DOM, or the ShadowRoot in the case of a shadow DOM.
dom-node-isconnected.title: Node.isConnected

dom-node-isdefaultnamespace.name: isDefaultNamespace
dom-node-isdefaultnamespace.summary: The Node.isDefaultNamespace() method accepts a namespace URI as an argument and returns a Boolean with a value of true if the namespace is the default namespace on the given node or false if not.
dom-node-isdefaultnamespace.title: Node.isDefaultNamespace()

dom-node-isequalnode.name: isEqualNode
dom-node-isequalnode.summary: The Node.isEqualNode() method tests whether two nodes are equal. Two nodes are equal when they have the same type, defining characteristics (for elements, this would be their ID, number of children, and so forth), its attributes match, and so on. The specific set of data points that must match varies depending on the types of the nodes.
dom-node-isequalnode.title: Node.isEqualNode()

dom-node-issamenode.name: isSameNode
dom-node-issamenode.summary: The isSameNode() method for Node objects tests whether two nodes are the same (that is, whether they reference the same object).
dom-node-issamenode.title: Node.isSameNode()

dom-node-lastchild.name: lastChild
dom-node-lastchild.summary: The Node.lastChild read-only property returns the last child of the node. If its parent is an element, then the child is generally an element node, a text node, or a comment node. It returns null if there are no child elements.
dom-node-lastchild.title: Node.lastChild

dom-node-lookupnamespaceuri.name: lookupNamespaceURI
dom-node-lookupnamespaceuri.summary: The Node.lookupNamespaceURI() method accepts a prefix and returns the namespace URI associated with it on the given node if found (and null if not).
dom-node-lookupnamespaceuri.title: Node.lookupNamespaceURI()

dom-node-nextsibling.name: nextSibling
dom-node-nextsibling.summary: The Node.nextSibling read-only property returns the node immediately following the specified one in their parent's childNodes, or returns null if the specified node is the last child in the parent element.
dom-node-nextsibling.title: Node.nextSibling

dom-node-nodename.name: nodeName
dom-node-nodename.summary: The nodeName read-only property returns the name of the current Node as a string.
dom-node-nodename.title: Node.nodeName

dom-node-nodetype.name: nodeType
dom-node-nodetype.summary: The read-only Node.nodeType property is an integer that identifies what the node is. It distinguishes different kind of nodes from each other, such as elements, text and comments.
dom-node-nodetype.title: Node.nodeType

dom-node-nodevalue.name: nodeValue
dom-node-nodevalue.summary: The nodeValue property of the Node interface returns or sets the value of the current node.
dom-node-nodevalue.title: Node.nodeValue

dom-node-normalize.name: normalize
dom-node-normalize.summary: The Node.normalize() method puts the specified node and all of its sub-tree into a "normalized" form. In a normalized sub-tree, no text nodes in the sub-tree are empty and there are no adjacent text nodes.
dom-node-normalize.title: Node.normalize()

dom-node-ownerdocument.name: ownerDocument
dom-node-ownerdocument.summary: The ownerDocument read-only property of the Node interface returns the top-level document object of the node.

firefox.notes: The ownerDocument of doctype nodes (that is, nodes for which Node.nodeType is Node.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE or 10) is no longer null. Instead, the ownerDocument is the document on which document.implementation.createDocumentType() was called.

firefox_android.notes: The ownerDocument of doctype nodes (that is, nodes for which Node.nodeType is Node.DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE or 10) is no longer null. Instead, the ownerDocument is the document on which document.implementation.createDocumentType() was called.

dom-node-ownerdocument.title: Node.ownerDocument

dom-node-parentelement.name: parentElement
dom-node-parentelement.summary: The Node.parentElement read-only property returns the DOM node's parent Element, or null if the node either has no parent, or its parent isn't a DOM Element.

ie.notes: Only supported on Element.

dom-node-parentelement.title: Node.parentElement

dom-node-parentnode.name: parentNode
dom-node-parentnode.summary: The Node.parentNode read-only property returns the parent of the specified node in the DOM tree.
dom-node-parentnode.title: Node.parentNode

dom-node-previoussibling.name: previousSibling
dom-node-previoussibling.summary: The Node.previousSibling read-only property returns the node immediately preceding the specified one in its parent's childNodes list, or null if the specified node is the first in that list.
dom-node-previoussibling.title: Node.previousSibling

dom-node-removechild.name: removeChild
dom-node-removechild.summary: The Node.removeChild() method removes a child node from the DOM and returns the removed node.
dom-node-removechild.title: Node.removeChild()

dom-node-replacechild.name: replaceChild
dom-node-replacechild.summary: The Node.replaceChild() method replaces a child node within the given (parent) node.
dom-node-replacechild.title: Node.replaceChild()

dom-node-textcontent.name: textContent
dom-node-textcontent.summary: The textContent property of the Node interface represents the text content of the node and its descendants.
dom-node-textcontent.title: Node.textContent

interface-node.name: Node
interface-node.summary: The DOM Node interface is an abstract base class upon which many other DOM API objects are based, thus letting those object types to be used similarly and often interchangeably.

chrome.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

chrome_android.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

opera.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

opera_android.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

safari.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

safari_ios.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

samsunginternet_android.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

webview_android.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

edge_blink.notes: WebKit and old versions of Blink incorrectly do not make Node inherit from EventTarget.

interface-node.title: Node

dom-nodefilter-acceptnode.name: acceptNode
dom-nodefilter-acceptnode.summary: The NodeFilter.acceptNode() method returns an unsigned short that will be used to tell if a given Node must be accepted or not by the NodeIterator or TreeWalker iteration algorithm. This method is expected to be written by the user of a NodeFilter. Possible return values are:
dom-nodefilter-acceptnode.title: NodeFilter.acceptNode()

interface-nodefilter.name: NodeFilter
interface-nodefilter.summary: A NodeFilter interface represents an object used to filter the nodes in a NodeIterator or TreeWalker. A NodeFilter knows nothing about the document or traversing nodes; it only knows how to evaluate a single node against the provided filter.
interface-nodefilter.title: NodeFilter

dom-nodeiterator-filter.name: filter
dom-nodeiterator-filter.summary: The NodeIterator.filter read-only method returns a NodeFilter object, that is an object implement an acceptNode(node) method, used to screen nodes.
dom-nodeiterator-filter.title: NodeIterator.filter

dom-nodeiterator-nextnode.name: nextNode
dom-nodeiterator-nextnode.summary: The NodeIterator.nextNode() method returns the next node in the set represented by the NodeIterator and advances the position of the iterator within the set.  The first call to nextNode() returns the first node in the set.
dom-nodeiterator-nextnode.title: NodeIterator.nextNode()

dom-nodeiterator-pointerbeforereferencen.name: pointerBeforeReferenceNode
dom-nodeiterator-pointerbeforereferencen.summary: The NodeIterator.pointerBeforeReferenceNode read-only property returns a Boolean flag that indicates whether the NodeFilter is anchored before (if this value is true) or after (if this value is false) the anchor node indicated by the NodeIterator.referenceNode property.
dom-nodeiterator-pointerbeforereferencen.title: NodeIterator.pointerBeforeReferenceNode

dom-nodeiterator-previousnode.name: previousNode
dom-nodeiterator-previousnode.summary: The NodeIterator.previousNode() method returns the previous node in the set represented by the NodeIterator and moves the position of the iterator backwards within the set.
dom-nodeiterator-previousnode.title: NodeIterator.previousNode()

dom-nodeiterator-referencenode.name: referenceNode
dom-nodeiterator-referencenode.summary: The NodeIterator.referenceNode read-only returns the Node to which the iterator is anchored; as new nodes are inserted, the iterator remains anchored to the reference node as specified by this property.
dom-nodeiterator-referencenode.title: NodeIterator.referenceNode

dom-nodeiterator-root.name: root
dom-nodeiterator-root.summary: The NodeIterator.root read-only property represents the Node that is the root of what the NodeIterator traverses.
dom-nodeiterator-root.title: NodeIterator.root

dom-nodeiterator-whattoshow.name: whatToShow
dom-nodeiterator-whattoshow.summary: The NodeIterator.whatToShow read-only property represents an unsigned integer representing a bitmask signifying what types of nodes should be returned by the NodeIterator.
dom-nodeiterator-whattoshow.title: NodeIterator.whatToShow

nodeiterator.name: NodeIterator
nodeiterator.summary: The NodeIterator interface represents an iterator over the members of a list of the nodes in a subtree of the DOM. The nodes will be returned in document order.
nodeiterator.title: NodeIterator

dom-nodelist-item.name: item
dom-nodelist-item.summary: Returns a node from a NodeList by index. This method doesn't throw exceptions as long as you provide arguments. A value of null is returned if the index is out of range, and a TypeError is thrown if no argument is provided.
dom-nodelist-item.title: NodeList.item()

dom-nodelist-length.name: length
dom-nodelist-length.summary: The NodeList.length property returns the number of items in a NodeList.
dom-nodelist-length.title: NodeList.length

interface-nodelist.name: NodeList
interface-nodelist.summary: NodeList objects are collections of nodes, usually returned by properties such as Node.childNodes and methods such as document.querySelectorAll().
interface-nodelist.title: NodeList

dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-nextelement.name: nextElementSibling
dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-nextelement.summary: The NonDocumentTypeChildNode.nextElementSibling read-only property returns the element immediately following the specified one in its parent's children list, or null if the specified element is the last one in the list.

ie.notes: Only implemented for Element, not for CharacterData. See polyfill.

dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-nextelement.title: NonDocumentTypeChildNode.nextElementSibling

dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-previousele.name: previousElementSibling
dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-previousele.summary: The NonDocumentTypeChildNode.previousElementSibling read-only property returns the Element immediately prior to the specified one in its parent's children list, or null if the specified element is the first one in the list.

ie.notes: Only implemented for Element, not for CharacterData. See polyfill.

dom-nondocumenttypechildnode-previousele.title: NonDocumentTypeChildNode.previousElementSibling

interface-nondocumenttypechildnode.name: NonDocumentTypeChildNode
interface-nondocumenttypechildnode.summary: The NonDocumentTypeChildNode interface contains methods that are particular to Node objects that can have a parent, but not suitable for DocumentType.
interface-nondocumenttypechildnode.title: NonDocumentTypeChildNode

dom-parentnode-append.name: append
dom-parentnode-append.summary: The ParentNode.append() method inserts a set of Node objects or DOMString objects after the last child of the ParentNode.
dom-parentnode-append.title: ParentNode.append()

dom-parentnode-childelementcount.name: childElementCount
dom-parentnode-childelementcount.summary: The ParentNode.childElementCount read-only property returns an unsigned long representing the number of child elements of the given element.
dom-parentnode-childelementcount.title: ParentNode.childElementCount

dom-parentnode-children.name: children
dom-parentnode-children.summary: The ParentNode property children is a read-only property that returns a live HTMLCollection which contains all of the child elements of the node upon which it was called.

ie.notes: Internet Explorer 6, 7 and 8 supported it, but erroneously includes Comment nodes.

dom-parentnode-children.title: ParentNode.children

dom-parentnode-firstelementchild.name: firstElementChild
dom-parentnode-firstelementchild.summary: The ParentNode.firstElementChild read-only property returns the object's first child Element, or null if there are no child elements.
dom-parentnode-firstelementchild.title: ParentNode.firstElementChild

dom-parentnode-lastelementchild.name: lastElementChild
dom-parentnode-lastelementchild.summary: The ParentNode.lastElementChild read-only property returns the object's last child Element or null if there are no child elements.
dom-parentnode-lastelementchild.title: ParentNode.lastElementChild

dom-parentnode-prepend.name: prepend
dom-parentnode-prepend.summary: The ParentNode.prepend() method inserts a set of Node objects or DOMString objects before the first child of the ParentNode. DOMString objects are inserted as equivalent Text nodes.
dom-parentnode-prepend.title: ParentNode.prepend()

dom-parentnode-replacechildren.name: replaceChildren
dom-parentnode-replacechildren.summary: The ParentNode.replaceChildren() method replaces the existing children of a Node with a specified new set of children. These can be DOMString or Node objects.
dom-parentnode-replacechildren.title: ParentNode.replaceChildren()

parentnode.name: ParentNode
parentnode.summary: The ParentNode mixin contains methods and properties that are common to all types of Node objects that can have children.
parentnode.title: ParentNode

processinginstruction.name: ProcessingInstruction
processinginstruction.summary: The ProcessingInstruction interface represents a processing instruction; that is, a Node which embeds an instruction targeting a specific application but that can be ignored by any other applications which don't recognize the instruction.
processinginstruction.title: ProcessingInstruction

dom-range-range.name: Range
dom-range-range.summary: The Range() constructor returns a newly created Range object whose start and end is the global Document object.
dom-range-range.title: Range()

dom-range-clonecontents.name: cloneContents
dom-range-clonecontents.summary: The Range.cloneContents() returns a DocumentFragment copying the objects of type Node included in the Range.
dom-range-clonecontents.title: Range.cloneContents()

dom-range-clonerange.name: cloneRange
dom-range-clonerange.summary: The Range.cloneRange() method returns a Range object with boundary points identical to the cloned Range.
dom-range-clonerange.title: Range.cloneRange()

dom-range-collapse.name: collapse
dom-range-collapse.summary: The Range.collapse() method collapses the Range to one of its boundary points.
dom-range-collapse.title: Range.collapse()

dom-range-commonancestorcontainer.name: commonAncestorContainer
dom-range-commonancestorcontainer.summary: The Range.commonAncestorContainer read-only property returns the deepest  or furthest down the document tree  Node that contains both boundary points of the Range. This means that if Range.startContainer and Range.endContainer both refer to the same node, this node is the common ancestor container.
dom-range-commonancestorcontainer.title: Range.commonAncestorContainer

dom-range-compareboundarypoints.name: compareBoundaryPoints
dom-range-compareboundarypoints.summary: The Range.compareBoundaryPoints() method compares the boundary points of the Range with those of another range.
dom-range-compareboundarypoints.title: Range.compareBoundaryPoints()

dom-range-comparepoint.name: comparePoint
dom-range-comparepoint.summary: The Range.comparePoint() method returns -1, 0, or 1 depending on whether the referenceNode is before, the same as, or after the Range.
dom-range-comparepoint.title: Range.comparePoint()

dom-range-deletecontents.name: deleteContents
dom-range-deletecontents.summary: The Range.deleteContents() method removes the contents of the Range from the Document.
dom-range-deletecontents.title: Range.deleteContents()

dom-range-detach.name: detach
dom-range-detach.summary: The Range.detach() method does nothing. It used to disable the Range object and enable the browser to release associated resources. The method has been kept for compatibility.

chrome.notes: Since April 2014 this method is a no-op in Chrome.

firefox.notes: Starting in Firefox 15.0, this method is a no-op and has no effect.

firefox_android.notes: Starting in Firefox 15.0, this method is a no-op and has no effect.

safari.notes: Since August 2015 this method is a no-op in WebKit-based browsers.

safari_ios.notes: Since August 2015 this method is a no-op in WebKit-based browsers.

edge_blink.notes: Since April 2014 this method is a no-op in Chrome.

dom-range-detach.title: Range.detach()

dom-range-extractcontents.name: extractContents
dom-range-extractcontents.summary: The Range.extractContents() method moves contents of the Range from the document tree into a DocumentFragment.
dom-range-extractcontents.title: Range.extractContents()

dom-range-insertnode.name: insertNode
dom-range-insertnode.summary: The Range.insertNode() method inserts a node at the start of the Range.
dom-range-insertnode.title: Range.insertNode()

dom-range-intersectsnode.name: intersectsNode
dom-range-intersectsnode.summary: The Range.intersectsNode() method returns a boolean indicating whether the given Node intersects the Range.
dom-range-intersectsnode.title: Range.intersectsNode()

dom-range-ispointinrange.name: isPointInRange
dom-range-ispointinrange.summary: The Range.isPointInRange() method returns a boolean indicating whether the given point is in the Range. It returns true if the point (cursor position) at offset within ReferenceNode is within this range.
dom-range-ispointinrange.title: Range.isPointInRange()

dom-range-selectnode.name: selectNode
dom-range-selectnode.summary: The Range.selectNode() method sets the Range to contain the Node and its contents. The parent Node of the start and end of the Range will be the same as the parent of the referenceNode.
dom-range-selectnode.title: Range.selectNode()

dom-range-selectnodecontents.name: selectNodeContents
dom-range-selectnodecontents.summary: The Range.selectNodeContents() method sets the Range to contain the contents of a Node.
dom-range-selectnodecontents.title: Range.selectNodeContents()

dom-range-setend.name: setEnd
dom-range-setend.summary: The Range.setEnd() method sets the end position of a Range to be located at the given offset into the specified node x.Setting the end point above (higher in the document) than the start point will result in a collapsed range with the start and end points both set to the specified end position.
dom-range-setend.title: Range.setEnd()

dom-range-setendafter.name: setEndAfter
dom-range-setendafter.summary: The Range.setEndAfter() method sets the end position of a Range relative to another Node. The parent Node of end of the Range will be the same as that for the referenceNode.
dom-range-setendafter.title: Range.setEndAfter()

dom-range-setendbefore.name: setEndBefore
dom-range-setendbefore.summary: The Range.setEndBefore() method sets the end position of a Range relative to another Node. The parent Node of end of the Range will be the same as that for the referenceNode.
dom-range-setendbefore.title: Range.setEndBefore()

dom-range-setstart.name: setStart
dom-range-setstart.summary: The Range.setStart() method sets the start position of a Range.
dom-range-setstart.title: Range.setStart()

dom-range-setstartafter.name: setStartAfter
dom-range-setstartafter.summary: The Range.setStartAfter() method sets the start position of a Range relative to a Node. The parent Node of the start of the Range will be the same as that for the referenceNode.
dom-range-setstartafter.title: Range.setStartAfter()

dom-range-setstartbefore.name: setStartBefore
dom-range-setstartbefore.summary: The Range.setStartBefore() method sets the start position of a Range relative to another Node. The parent Node of the start of the Range will be the same as that for the referenceNode.
dom-range-setstartbefore.title: Range.setStartBefore()

dom-range-surroundcontents.name: surroundContents
dom-range-surroundcontents.summary: The Range.surroundContents() method moves content of the Range into a new node, placing the new node at the start of the specified range.
dom-range-surroundcontents.title: Range.surroundContents()

dom-range-stringifier.name: toString
dom-range-stringifier.summary: The Range.toString() method is a stringifier returning the text of the Range.
dom-range-stringifier.title: Range.toString()

interface-range.name: Range
interface-range.summary: The Range interface represents a fragment of a document that can contain nodes and parts of text nodes.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 13, the Range object throws a DOMException as defined in DOM 4, instead of a RangeException defined in prior specifications.

firefox_android.notes: Starting with Firefox 13, the Range object throws a DOMException as defined in DOM 4, instead of a RangeException defined in prior specifications.

interface-range.title: Range

dom-shadowroot-host.name: host
dom-shadowroot-host.summary: The host read-only property of the ShadowRoot returns a reference to the DOM element the ShadowRoot is attached to.
dom-shadowroot-host.title: ShadowRoot.host

dom-shadowroot-mode.name: mode
dom-shadowroot-mode.summary: The mode property of the ShadowRoot specifies its mode  either open or closed. This defines whether or not the shadow root's internal features are accessible from JavaScript.
dom-shadowroot-mode.title: ShadowRoot.mode

interface-shadowroot.name: ShadowRoot
interface-shadowroot.summary: The ShadowRoot interface of the Shadow DOM API is the root node of a DOM subtree that is rendered separately from a document's main DOM tree.
interface-shadowroot.title: ShadowRoot

dom-slotable-assignedslot.name: assignedSlot
dom-slotable-assignedslot.summary: The assignedSlot read-only property of the Slottable interface returns an HTMLSlotElement representing the <slot> element the node is inserted in.
dom-slotable-assignedslot.title: Slottable: assignedSlot

dom-slotable-assignedslot.name: assignedSlot
dom-slotable-assignedslot.summary: The assignedSlot property of the Text interface returns the HTMLSlotElement object associated with the element.
dom-slotable-assignedslot.title: HTMLSlotElement.assignedSlot

slotable.name: Slottable
slotable.summary: The Slottable mixin defines features that allow nodes to become the contents of a <slot> element  the following features are included in both Element and Text.
slotable.title: Slottable

dom-staticrange-staticrange.name: StaticRange
dom-staticrange-staticrange.summary: The StaticRange() constructor creates a new StaticRange object representing a span of content within the DOM.
dom-staticrange-staticrange.title: StaticRange.StaticRange()

interface-staticrange.name: StaticRange
interface-staticrange.summary: The DOM StaticRange interface extends AbstractRange to provide a method to specify a range of content in the DOM whose contents don't update to reflect changes which occur within the DOM tree.

firefox.notes: In Firefox, StaticRange can currently only be used by browser-internal code or code with enhanced permissions; it is not yet exposed to the web.

interface-staticrange.title: StaticRange

dom-text-text.name: Text
dom-text-text.summary: The Text() constructor returns a newly created Text object with the optional DOMString given in parameter as its textual content.
dom-text-text.title: Text()

dom-text-splittext.name: splitText
dom-text-splittext.summary: The Text.splitText() method breaks the Text node into two nodes at the specified offset, keeping both nodes in the tree as siblings.

chrome.notes: Before Chrome 30, the offset argument was optional.

chrome_android.notes: Before Chrome 30, the offset argument was optional.

opera.notes: Before Opera 17, the offset argument was optional.

opera_android.notes: Before Opera 17, the offset argument was optional.

samsunginternet_android.notes: Before Samsung Internet 2.0, the offset argument was optional.

webview_android.notes: Before version 4.4, the offset argument was optional.

edge_blink.notes: Before Chrome 30, the offset argument was optional.

dom-text-splittext.title: Text.splitText()

dom-text-wholetext.name: wholeText
dom-text-wholetext.summary: The Text.wholeText read-only property returns the full text of all Text nodes logically adjacent to the node.
dom-text-wholetext.title: Text.wholeText

text.name: Text
text.summary: The Text interface represents the textual content of Element or Attr.
text.title: Text

dom-treewalker-currentnode.name: currentNode
dom-treewalker-currentnode.summary: The TreeWalker.currentNode property represents the Node on which the TreeWalker is currently pointing at.
dom-treewalker-currentnode.title: TreeWalker.currentNode

dom-treewalker-filter.name: filter
dom-treewalker-filter.summary: The TreeWalker.filter read-only property returns a NodeFilter that is the filtering object associated with the TreeWalker.
dom-treewalker-filter.title: TreeWalker.filter

dom-treewalker-firstchild.name: firstChild
dom-treewalker-firstchild.summary: The TreeWalker.firstChild() method moves the current Node to the first visible child of the current node, and returns the found child. It also moves the current node to this child. If no such child exists, returns null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-firstchild.title: TreeWalker.firstChild()

dom-treewalker-lastchild.name: lastChild
dom-treewalker-lastchild.summary: The TreeWalker.lastChild() method moves the current Node to the last visible child of the current node, and returns the found child. It also moves the current node to this child. If no such child exists, returns null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-lastchild.title: TreeWalker.lastChild()

dom-treewalker-nextnode.name: nextNode
dom-treewalker-nextnode.summary: The TreeWalker.nextNode() method moves the current Node to the next visible node in the document order, and returns the found node. It also moves the current node to this one. If no such node exists, returns null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-nextnode.title: TreeWalker.nextNode()

dom-treewalker-nextsibling.name: nextSibling
dom-treewalker-nextsibling.summary: The TreeWalker.nextSibling() method moves the current Node to its next sibling, if any, and returns the found sibling. If there is no such node, return null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-nextsibling.title: TreeWalker.nextSibling()

dom-treewalker-parentnode.name: parentNode
dom-treewalker-parentnode.summary: The TreeWalker.parentNode() method moves the current Node to the first visible ancestor node in the document order, and returns the found node. If no such node exists, or if it is above the TreeWalker's root node, returns null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-parentnode.title: TreeWalker.parentNode()

dom-treewalker-previousnode.name: previousNode
dom-treewalker-previousnode.summary: The TreeWalker.previousNode() method moves the current Node to the previous visible node in the document order, and returns the found node. It also moves the current node to this one. If no such node exists,or if it is before that the root node defined at the object construction, returns null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-previousnode.title: TreeWalker.previousNode()

dom-treewalker-previoussibling.name: previousSibling
dom-treewalker-previoussibling.summary: The TreeWalker.previousSibling() method moves the current Node to its previous sibling, if any, and returns the found sibling. If there is no such node, return null and the current node is not changed.
dom-treewalker-previoussibling.title: TreeWalker.previousSibling()

dom-treewalker-root.name: root
dom-treewalker-root.summary: The TreeWalker.root read-only property returns the node that is the root of what the TreeWalker traverses.
